<!-- ═══ T1: CLOUD COMPUTING INTRO ═══ -->
<div id="t1">
<div class="topic"><div class="tnum">1</div><div><div class="ttitle">Cloud Computing — Introduction</div><div class="tsub">Definition · Characteristics · Benefits · Applications · Evolution</div></div><span class="badge br">ALL Papers</span></div>
<div class="pyq">📋 Asked in: June'22, Dec'22, June'23, Dec'23, June'24, Dec'24, June'25, Dec'25 — definition + characteristics + applications appear in every single paper</div>
<div class="sec">💡 Understand It Simply</div>
<div class="understand"><div class="ul">What it actually means</div><p>Cloud computing is like renting a house instead of buying one. You don't own the servers — you just pay for what you use, when you use it. Any time, anywhere, from any device. The "cloud" is just someone else's computer that you access over the internet. Instead of buying expensive hardware, you use Amazon's or Google's servers and pay per hour.</p></div>
<div class="sec">🔑 Keywords to Memorise</div>
<div class="keywords"><div class="kl">These words MUST appear in your answer</div>
<div class="kw-grid"><span class="kw">On-demand self-service</span><span class="kw">Broad network access</span><span class="kw">Resource pooling</span><span class="kw">Rapid elasticity</span><span class="kw">Measured service</span><span class="kw">Pay-per-use</span><span class="kw">Scalability</span><span class="kw">Ubiquitous access</span><span class="kw">NIST definition</span><span class="kw">IT service-centric</span></div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 5-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Cloud Computing — Definition and Characteristics</span><span class="m5">5 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Cloud Computing is a model for enabling ubiquitous, convenient, <span class="kh">on-demand self-service</span> access to a shared pool of configurable computing resources over the internet, which can be rapidly provisioned and released with minimal management effort (NIST definition).</p>
<p><strong>Five Key Characteristics (NIST):</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>On-demand self-service:</strong> Users can provision computing resources without requiring human interaction with the service provider</li>
<li><strong>Broad network access:</strong> Services available over the network and accessible through standard mechanisms from any device</li>
<li><strong>Resource pooling:</strong> Provider's resources pooled to serve multiple consumers using a multi-tenant model</li>
<li><strong>Rapid elasticity:</strong> Resources can be elastically provisioned and released to scale rapidly with demand</li>
<li><strong>Measured service:</strong> Resource usage can be monitored, controlled, and reported — enabling <span class="kh">pay-per-use</span> billing</li>
</ul>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 10-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Cloud Computing — Definition, Characteristics, Benefits, and Applications</span><span class="m10">10 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Cloud Computing is a model enabling <span class="kh">on-demand self-service</span> access to shared computing resources over the internet, with <span class="kh">pay-per-use</span> billing (NIST definition). It transforms how organisations purchase and use computing infrastructure.</p>
<p><strong>Five Key Characteristics:</strong> On-demand self-service, <span class="kh">Broad network access</span> (any device, anywhere), <span class="kh">Resource pooling</span> (multi-tenant shared infrastructure), <span class="kh">Rapid elasticity</span> (scale up/down instantly), <span class="kh">Measured service</span> (metered billing).</p>
<p><strong>Benefits of Cloud Computing:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Cost Reduction:</strong> No upfront capital investment in hardware; pay only for what you use</li>
<li><strong>Scalability:</strong> Instantly scale resources up or down as business demand changes</li>
<li><strong>Accessibility:</strong> Access from anywhere with internet — supports remote work</li>
<li><strong>Disaster Recovery:</strong> Data backed up across multiple servers automatically</li>
<li><strong>Automatic Updates:</strong> Service provider handles maintenance and software updates</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Applications:</strong> E-commerce (Amazon, Flipkart), E-Governance (digital services), Healthcare (patient records, telemedicine), Entertainment (Netflix streaming), Education (online learning platforms), Business productivity (Google Workspace, Microsoft 365).</p>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 20-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Cloud Computing — Evolution, Characteristics, Benefits, Applications, Challenges</span><span class="m20">20 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Cloud Computing provides <span class="kh">on-demand self-service</span> access to a shared pool of configurable computing resources (networks, servers, storage, applications) over the internet, with minimal management effort and <span class="kh">pay-per-use</span> billing (NIST definition).</p>
<p><strong>Evolution of Cloud Computing:</strong> The concept began in 1960s when John McCarthy proposed time-sharing of mainframes. In 1969, J.C.R. Licklider proposed an "Intergalactic Computer Network." In 1997, Prof. Ramnath Chellappa first formally defined "cloud computing." In 1999, Salesforce.com launched the first SaaS application. In 2006, Amazon launched EC2 (Elastic Compute Cloud) and S3, establishing the modern cloud era.</p>
<p><strong>Five Characteristics (NIST):</strong> <span class="kh">On-demand self-service</span>, <span class="kh">Broad network access</span>, <span class="kh">Resource pooling</span> (multi-tenant), <span class="kh">Rapid elasticity</span>, <span class="kh">Measured service</span> (pay-per-use).</p>
<p><strong>Benefits:</strong> Cost reduction (no capital expenditure), Scalability, Accessibility from anywhere, Disaster recovery, Automatic updates, Green IT (reduced power consumption through shared infrastructure).</p>
<p><strong>Applications:</strong> E-commerce, E-Governance, Scientific computing (simulations), Healthcare (records management), Entertainment streaming, Financial services, Education platforms.</p>
<p><strong>Challenges of Cloud Computing:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Security and Privacy:</strong> Data stored on third-party servers raises confidentiality concerns</li>
<li><strong>Vendor Lock-in:</strong> Difficult to migrate data and applications between providers</li>
<li><strong>Internet Dependency:</strong> Cloud services are unusable without reliable internet connectivity</li>
<li><strong>Scaling Resources:</strong> Sudden demand surges may cause resource contention</li>
<li><strong>Compliance:</strong> Regulatory requirements differ across regions for data storage</li>
</ul>
</div></div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ T2: DEPLOYMENT MODELS ═══ -->
<div id="t2">
<div class="topic"><div class="tnum">2</div><div><div class="ttitle">Cloud Deployment Models</div><div class="tsub">Public · Private · Community · Hybrid · When to Use Which</div></div><span class="badge br">ALL Papers</span></div>
<div class="pyq">📋 Asked in: June'22, Dec'22, June'23, June'24, Dec'24, June'25, Dec'25 — "define and explain four deployment models" is the most repeated single question in the entire paper</div>
<div class="sec">💡 Understand It Simply</div>
<div class="understand"><div class="ul">What it actually means</div><p>Think of cloud deployment like office space options. Public cloud = co-working space (anyone can use it, cheapest, shared). Private cloud = your own office (only your company, most expensive, most control). Community cloud = shared office for a specific industry (e.g., all hospitals sharing one secure cloud). Hybrid cloud = you have your own office but also rent extra co-working desks when busy.</p></div>
<div class="sec">🔑 Keywords to Memorise</div>
<div class="keywords"><div class="kl">These words MUST appear in your answer</div>
<div class="kw-grid"><span class="kw">Public cloud — anyone can access</span><span class="kw">Private cloud — single organisation</span><span class="kw">Community cloud — shared specific group</span><span class="kw">Hybrid cloud — combination</span><span class="kw">Multi-tenancy</span><span class="kw">On-premises</span><span class="kw">Third-party provider</span><span class="kw">Scalability vs control tradeoff</span></div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 5-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Cloud Deployment Models — Brief Definitions</span><span class="m5">5 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<ul>
<li><strong>Public Cloud:</strong> Infrastructure operated by a <span class="kh">third-party provider</span>, made available to the general public. <span class="kh">Anyone can access</span> over the internet. Examples: AWS, Google Cloud, Azure. Low cost, high scalability, lower security control.</li>
<li><strong>Private Cloud:</strong> Infrastructure operated exclusively for a <span class="kh">single organisation</span>. Can be on-premise or hosted by a provider. High security, full control, expensive. Examples: Government agencies, banks.</li>
<li><strong>Community Cloud:</strong> Shared by several organisations with common concerns (e.g., security policy, compliance). Example: Multiple hospitals sharing a healthcare cloud.</li>
<li><strong>Hybrid Cloud:</strong> <span class="kh">Combination</span> of public and private clouds that remain distinct but are bound together. Organisation uses private cloud for sensitive data and public cloud for scalable workloads.</li>
</ul>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 10-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Deployment Models — With Characteristics and Suitability</span><span class="m10">10 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Cloud deployment models describe how cloud infrastructure is set up and who has access to it.</p>
<table>
<tr><th>Model</th><th>Who Accesses</th><th>Managed By</th><th>Key Feature</th><th>Example</th></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Public</strong></td><td>General public — <span class="kh">anyone can access</span></td><td><span class="kh">Third-party provider</span></td><td>Highly scalable, lowest cost, less control</td><td>AWS, Google Cloud</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Private</strong></td><td><span class="kh">Single organisation</span> only</td><td>Organisation itself or dedicated provider</td><td>Maximum security and control, higher cost</td><td>Bank's internal cloud</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Community</strong></td><td>A specific group with shared interests</td><td>Community members or third party</td><td>Shared cost, common compliance requirements</td><td>Healthcare sector cloud</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Hybrid</strong></td><td><span class="kh">Combination</span> — sensitive data private, scalable loads public</td><td>Both provider and organisation</td><td>Flexibility, partial security</td><td>Enterprise with seasonal peaks</td></tr>
</table>
<p><strong>Suitability:</strong> Public cloud is best for startups, testing environments, or applications needing high scalability with budget constraints. Private cloud is best for organisations with strict compliance/security needs (banks, government). Community cloud suits groups with shared regulatory frameworks (hospitals, law firms). Hybrid cloud is best for enterprises needing to keep sensitive data <span class="kh">on-premises</span> while bursting to public cloud for peak demand.</p>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 20-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Deployment Models — Complete with Comparison Table and Network Connectivity</span><span class="m20">20 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Cloud Deployment Models describe the type of access, management, and ownership of cloud infrastructure. The four models are: Public, Private, Community, and Hybrid.</p>
<table>
<tr><th>Feature</th><th>Public</th><th>Private</th><th>Community</th><th>Hybrid</th></tr>
<tr><td>Access</td><td>Anyone — <span class="kh">anyone can access</span></td><td><span class="kh">Single organisation</span></td><td>Specific group</td><td><span class="kh">Combination</span></td></tr>
<tr><td>Management</td><td><span class="kh">Third-party provider</span></td><td>Organisation or dedicated provider</td><td>Members or third party</td><td>Both</td></tr>
<tr><td>Cost</td><td>Lowest (pay-per-use)</td><td>Highest (own infrastructure)</td><td>Shared cost</td><td>Medium</td></tr>
<tr><td>Security</td><td>Lower (shared)</td><td>Highest</td><td>Medium-high</td><td>Partial security</td></tr>
<tr><td>Scalability</td><td>Highest</td><td>Limited</td><td>Moderate</td><td>High</td></tr>
<tr><td>Example</td><td>AWS, Azure</td><td>Bank private cloud</td><td>Healthcare cloud</td><td>Enterprise hybrid</td></tr>
</table>
<p><strong>Network Connectivity in Cloud Deployment:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Public Inter Cloud Networking:</strong> Connecting cloud environments from different public providers (e.g., AWS to Google Cloud) over the public internet using standard protocols</li>
<li><strong>Private Intra Cloud Networking:</strong> Internal networking within a single cloud provider's infrastructure — using Virtual Private Cloud (VPC) with dedicated private network segments for isolation and security</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>When to use which model:</strong> Public cloud for startups and applications with variable workloads needing maximum scalability. Private cloud for banking, government, and defence where data sovereignty and compliance are non-negotiable. Community cloud for groups sharing regulatory requirements (hospitals sharing HIPAA-compliant infrastructure). Hybrid cloud for enterprises keeping sensitive workloads <span class="kh">on-premises</span> while bursting capacity to public cloud during peak periods — balancing the <span class="kh">scalability vs control tradeoff</span>.</p>
</div></div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ T3: SERVICE DELIVERY ═══ -->
<div id="t3">
<div class="topic"><div class="tnum">3</div><div><div class="ttitle">Service Delivery Models — IaaS, PaaS, SaaS</div><div class="tsub">Infrastructure · Platform · Software · Differences · Examples</div></div><span class="badge br">ALL Papers</span></div>
<div class="pyq">📋 Asked in: June'22, Dec'22, June'23, Dec'23, June'24, Dec'24, June'25, Dec'25 — appears in EVERY paper in various forms</div>
<div class="sec">💡 Understand It Simply</div>
<div class="understand"><div class="ul">What it actually means</div><p>Think of building a restaurant. IaaS = you rent the empty building (raw infrastructure — servers, storage, network) and do everything yourself. PaaS = you rent the building with kitchen equipment already installed (platform for developers — just write code). SaaS = you just walk into someone else's restaurant and eat (ready-made software — just use it). Each layer abstracts more complexity away from you.</p></div>
<div class="sec">🔑 Keywords to Memorise</div>
<div class="keywords"><div class="kl">These words MUST appear in your answer</div>
<div class="kw-grid"><span class="kw">IaaS — virtualized infrastructure</span><span class="kw">PaaS — development environment</span><span class="kw">SaaS — cloud-based application</span><span class="kw">Pay-per-use billing</span><span class="kw">Vendor lock-in (PaaS)</span><span class="kw">Multi-tenancy (SaaS)</span><span class="kw">No client-side installation</span><span class="kw">Elastic resources</span></div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 5-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>IaaS, PaaS, SaaS — Brief Definitions</span><span class="m5">5 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<ul>
<li><strong>IaaS (Infrastructure as a Service):</strong> Provides <span class="kh">virtualized infrastructure</span> — servers, storage, networking — on demand. Users manage OS and applications. <span class="kh">Pay-per-use billing</span>. Example: Amazon EC2, Google Compute Engine.</li>
<li><strong>PaaS (Platform as a Service):</strong> Provides a <span class="kh">development environment</span> — OS, middleware, runtime, databases — for developers to build and deploy applications without managing infrastructure. Example: Google App Engine, Heroku.</li>
<li><strong>SaaS (Software as a Service):</strong> Provides ready-to-use <span class="kh">cloud-based application</span> accessed via browser. <span class="kh">No client-side installation</span> required. Uses <span class="kh">multi-tenancy</span>. Example: Gmail, Salesforce, Microsoft 365.</li>
</ul>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 10-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Service Delivery Models — Full Comparison with Advantages and Disadvantages</span><span class="m10">10 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Cloud Service Delivery Models define the type of service offered to consumers, determining what the provider manages and what the user manages.</p>
<table>
<tr><th>Feature</th><th>IaaS</th><th>PaaS</th><th>SaaS</th></tr>
<tr><td>Full Name</td><td><span class="kh">Infrastructure as a Service</span></td><td><span class="kh">Platform as a Service</span></td><td><span class="kh">Software as a Service</span></td></tr>
<tr><td>What Provider Gives</td><td>Servers, storage, networking (virtualized)</td><td>Runtime, middleware, OS, databases</td><td>Complete ready-to-use application</td></tr>
<tr><td>User Manages</td><td>OS, middleware, applications</td><td>Applications and data only</td><td>Nothing — just uses the app</td></tr>
<tr><td>Target Users</td><td>System administrators, IT teams</td><td>Developers</td><td>End users, businesses</td></tr>
<tr><td>Example</td><td>Amazon EC2, Google Compute</td><td>Google App Engine, Heroku</td><td>Gmail, Salesforce, Dropbox</td></tr>
<tr><td>Billing</td><td><span class="kh">Pay-per-use billing</span></td><td>Subscription or usage</td><td>Subscription per user</td></tr>
</table>
<p><strong>IaaS Advantages:</strong> Reduced cost (no hardware purchase), <span class="kh">Elastic resources</span> (scale up/down), Better resource utilisation, Supports green IT.<br>
<strong>IaaS Disadvantage:</strong> Security risks through hypervisors.</p>
<p><strong>PaaS Advantages:</strong> Faster app development, Reduces investment cost, Team collaboration support, Scalable applications.<br>
<strong>PaaS Disadvantage:</strong> <span class="kh">Vendor lock-in</span> — difficult to move to another provider.</p>
<p><strong>SaaS Advantages:</strong> <span class="kh">No client-side installation</span>, Cost savings (subscription), Disaster recovery built-in, <span class="kh">Multi-tenancy</span> improves resource utilisation.<br>
<strong>SaaS Disadvantage:</strong> Security and data control concerns.</p>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 20-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Service Delivery Models — Complete with XaaS and Real Examples</span><span class="m20">20 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Cloud Computing offers services through three primary delivery models — IaaS, PaaS, and SaaS — plus additional specialised services collectively called XaaS (Everything as a Service).</p>
<p><strong>IaaS — Virtualized Infrastructure:</strong> Provides raw computing infrastructure (servers, storage, networking) as a service with <span class="kh">pay-per-use billing</span>. The user manages everything above the hardware. Key features: charging based on usage, reduced cost, <span class="kh">elastic resources</span>, better resource utilisation. Real examples: Amazon EC2 for compute, Amazon S3 for storage, Google Compute Engine.</p>
<p><strong>PaaS — Virtualized Development Environment:</strong> Provides a complete <span class="kh">development environment</span> — programming languages, application platforms, database, testing tools — allowing developers to build, test, and deploy applications without infrastructure management. Key features: faster development, team collaboration, produces scalable applications. Disadvantage: <span class="kh">vendor lock-in</span> due to proprietary tools. Real examples: Google App Engine, Heroku, Scalingo.</p>
<p><strong>SaaS — Cloud-Based Application:</strong> Delivers complete applications over the internet. <span class="kh">No client-side installation</span>. Uses <span class="kh">multi-tenancy</span> — one application instance serves many customers. Features: business services, social media networks, document management, e-mail services, dynamic scaling, disaster recovery. Real examples: Gmail, Salesforce CRM, Microsoft 365, Dropbox.</p>
<p><strong>Additional Services (XaaS):</strong> Security as a Service (SECaaS) — cloud-delivered security; Storage as a Service; Database as a Service (DBaaS); Load Balancing as a Service (LBaaS); Identity Management as a Service.</p>
<table>
<tr><th></th><th>IaaS</th><th>PaaS</th><th>SaaS</th></tr>
<tr><td>User controls</td><td>OS + Apps</td><td>Apps only</td><td>Nothing</td></tr>
<tr><td>Provider controls</td><td>Hardware only</td><td>Hardware + Platform</td><td>Everything</td></tr>
<tr><td>Flexibility</td><td>Maximum</td><td>Medium</td><td>Minimum</td></tr>
</table>
</div></div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ T4: CLOUD ARCHITECTURE ═══ -->
<div id="t4">
<div class="topic"><div class="tnum">4</div><div><div class="ttitle">Cloud Architecture — 4 Layers</div><div class="tsub">Client Access · Internet Connectivity · Service Management · Physical Resources</div></div><span class="badge by">5+ Papers</span></div>
<div class="pyq">📋 Asked in: June'22 (block diagram), Dec'23 (explain all 4 layers), June'24 — "4 levels in cloud architecture" with block diagram is a favourite</div>
<div class="sec">💡 Understand It Simply</div>
<div class="understand"><div class="ul">What it actually means</div><p>Cloud architecture is like a building with 4 floors. Ground floor = the actual physical machines and hardware. 2nd floor = the services that manage how those resources are used. 3rd floor = internet connectivity that lets users reach the cloud. Top floor = the client devices people use to access everything. Each floor serves the one above it.</p></div>
<div class="sec">🔑 Keywords to Memorise</div>
<div class="keywords"><div class="kl">These words MUST appear in your answer</div>
<div class="kw-grid"><span class="kw">Client access layer</span><span class="kw">Internet connectivity layer</span><span class="kw">Cloud service management layer</span><span class="kw">Layer of physical resources</span><span class="kw">Web browser / thin client</span><span class="kw">VPN / firewall</span><span class="kw">Virtualization</span><span class="kw">Servers storage network</span></div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 5-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Cloud Architecture — 4 Layers Quick Version</span><span class="m5">5 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<ul>
<li><strong>Client Access Layer:</strong> The topmost layer — where users interact with cloud services via web browsers, desktop applications, or mobile apps (thin clients)</li>
<li><strong>Internet Connectivity Layer:</strong> Provides secure network connection between clients and cloud using VPN, firewalls, and internet protocols</li>
<li><strong>Cloud Service Management Layer:</strong> Manages IaaS, PaaS, SaaS services — handles billing, monitoring, resource allocation, and SLA management</li>
<li><strong>Layer of Physical Resources:</strong> The bottommost layer — actual physical servers, storage devices, networking hardware, and data centres that run everything</li>
</ul>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 10-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Cloud Architecture — 4 Layers with Block Diagram Description</span><span class="m10">10 Marks</span></div>
