<!-- ═══ T5: VIRTUALIZATION ═══ -->
<div id="t5">
<div class="topic"><div class="tnum">5</div><div><div class="ttitle">Virtualization &amp; Hypervisors</div><div class="tsub">Types · Full · Para · Hardware-Assisted · Type-1 vs Type-2 Hypervisor</div></div><span class="badge br">7+ Papers</span></div>
<div class="pyq">📋 Asked in: June'22, Dec'22, June'23, Dec'23, June'24, Dec'24, June'25, Dec'25 — "virtualization types" and "hypervisor type-1 vs type-2" appear in almost every paper</div>
<div class="sec">💡 Understand It Simply</div>
<div class="understand"><div class="ul">What it actually means</div><p>Virtualization means running multiple "virtual computers" inside one physical computer at the same time. Like running Windows and Linux simultaneously on one laptop using VMware. Each virtual machine (VM) thinks it's the only OS running — but the hypervisor (the "traffic controller" software) tricks them all. This is how cloud providers like AWS serve thousands of customers on the same physical servers.</p></div>
<div class="sec">🔑 Keywords to Memorise</div>
<div class="keywords"><div class="kl">These words MUST appear in your answer</div>
<div class="kw-grid"><span class="kw">Underlying abstraction</span><span class="kw">Host machine</span><span class="kw">Guest OS / VM</span><span class="kw">Hypervisor (VMM)</span><span class="kw">Full virtualization — binary translation</span><span class="kw">Para-virtualization — modified OS</span><span class="kw">Hardware-assisted — CPU support</span><span class="kw">Type-1 Bare metal</span><span class="kw">Type-2 Hosted</span><span class="kw">Isolation</span><span class="kw">Sharing of resources</span></div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 5-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Virtualization — Definition and Types</span><span class="m5">5 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Virtualization is a key technology that creates an <span class="kh">underlying abstraction</span> layer over physical hardware, allowing multiple virtual machines (VMs) to run simultaneously on one physical <span class="kh">host machine</span>. The <span class="kh">Hypervisor (VMM)</span> — Virtual Machine Monitor — manages all VMs and allocates resources.</p>
<p><strong>Three Types of Server-Level Virtualization:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Full Virtualization:</strong> <span class="kh">Binary translation</span> technique; Guest OS runs unmodified. Hypervisor traps and translates all privileged instructions. Example: VMware.</li>
<li><strong>Para-Virtualization:</strong> <span class="kh">Modified OS</span> is used — the guest OS is aware it's being virtualised. More efficient than full virtualization. Example: Xen.</li>
<li><strong>Hardware-Assisted Virtualization:</strong> Uses <span class="kh">CPU support</span> (Intel VT-x or AMD-V) to run VMs without binary translation or OS modification. Best performance.</li>
</ul>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 10-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Virtualization — Complete with Hypervisor Types and Comparison</span><span class="m10">10 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Virtualization creates an <span class="kh">underlying abstraction</span> over physical hardware, allowing multiple <span class="kh">Guest OS / VMs</span> to run on one <span class="kh">host machine</span>, managed by a <span class="kh">Hypervisor (VMM)</span>.</p>
<p><strong>Features of Virtualization Environment:</strong> <span class="kh">Sharing of resources</span> among VMs, <span class="kh">Isolation</span> (VMs run independently), Aggregation (combine resources of different machines), Emulation (run different OS types), Security advancement.</p>
<p><strong>Three Server-Level Virtualization Types:</strong></p>
<table>
<tr><th>Type</th><th>How it Works</th><th>Guest OS</th><th>Performance</th></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Full Virtualization</strong></td><td><span class="kh">Binary translation</span> — hypervisor translates privileged instructions at runtime</td><td>Runs completely unmodified</td><td>Lower (translation overhead)</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Para-Virtualization</strong></td><td>Guest OS <span class="kh">modified OS</span> to make "hypercalls" directly to hypervisor</td><td>Must be modified to be aware of virtualisation</td><td>Higher (direct calls, no translation)</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Hardware-Assisted</strong></td><td>Uses special <span class="kh">CPU support</span> (Intel VT-x / AMD-V) — hardware handles privilege trapping</td><td>Runs unmodified</td><td>Best (hardware does the work)</td></tr>
</table>
<p><strong>Type-1 vs Type-2 Hypervisor:</strong></p>
<table>
<tr><th>Feature</th><th>Type-1 (Bare-Metal)</th><th>Type-2 (Hosted)</th></tr>
<tr><td>Runs on</td><td>Directly on physical hardware — <span class="kh">Type-1 Bare metal</span></td><td>On top of a host OS — <span class="kh">Type-2 Hosted</span></td></tr>
<tr><td>Performance</td><td>Higher (direct hardware access)</td><td>Lower (goes through host OS)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Use Case</td><td>Enterprise data centres, cloud providers</td><td>Development, testing on personal computers</td></tr>
<tr><td>Examples</td><td>VMware ESXi, Microsoft Hyper-V, Xen</td><td>VirtualBox, VMware Workstation</td></tr>
</table>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 20-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Virtualization — Complete: Abstraction, All Types, Advantages, Desktop Level</span><span class="m20">20 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Virtualization is a key technology that creates an <span class="kh">underlying abstraction</span> layer over available system hardware, allowing the creation of virtual environments similar to the real environment. The <span class="kh">Hypervisor (VMM)</span> acts as the middleware managing all <span class="kh">Guest OS / VMs</span> running on one <span class="kh">host machine</span>.</p>
<p><strong>Virtualizing Physical Computing Resources:</strong> Virtualization layer acts as middleware creating virtual environments. It enables: <span class="kh">Sharing of resources</span> (multiple VMs on one host), Aggregation (combining distributed resources), <span class="kh">Isolation</span> (VMs run independently without interference), Emulation (running different OS types), Security advancement (compromise of one VM doesn't affect others).</p>
<p><strong>Advantages of Virtualization:</strong> Server consolidation (fewer physical servers needed), Reducing power consumption, Lower hardware cost, Better availability and fault tolerance, Faster provisioning of new environments, Flexibility for IT administrators.</p>
<p><strong>Three Server-Level Virtualization Types:</strong></p>
<table>
<tr><th>Type</th><th>Mechanism</th><th>Guest OS Modified?</th><th>Performance</th><th>Example</th></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Full Virtualization</strong></td><td><span class="kh">Binary translation</span> of privileged instructions at runtime</td><td>No — unmodified</td><td>Lower overhead</td><td>VMware ESXi</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Para-Virtualization</strong></td><td>Guest OS uses <span class="kh">modified OS</span> to call hypervisor via hypercalls</td><td>Yes — must be ported</td><td>More efficient</td><td>Xen</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Hardware-Assisted</strong></td><td>Special <span class="kh">CPU support</span> (Intel VT-x/AMD-V) traps privileged ops in hardware</td><td>No — unmodified</td><td>Best performance</td><td>KVM</td></tr>
</table>
<p><strong>Type-1 vs Type-2 Hypervisor:</strong> Type-1 (<span class="kh">Type-1 Bare metal</span>) — runs directly on hardware, used in enterprise data centres and cloud providers, highest performance. Type-2 (<span class="kh">Type-2 Hosted</span>) — runs on top of a host OS (e.g., Windows), used for testing and development on personal computers, lower performance due to extra OS layer.</p>
<p><strong>Desktop Level Virtualization:</strong> Allows users to run multiple desktop environments on one machine. Types include: Virtual Desktop Infrastructure (VDI) where desktop OS runs on server-side VM and is streamed to thin client; and Local Desktop Virtualization where VM runs locally. Benefits: centralised management, data security (data stays on server), easy disaster recovery.</p>
</div></div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ T6: VM SIZING ═══ -->
<div id="t6">
<div class="topic"><div class="tnum">6</div><div><div class="ttitle">VM Sizing</div><div class="tsub">Definition · Two Ways — Vertical and Horizontal Sizing</div></div><span class="badge by">5+ Papers</span></div>
<div class="pyq">📋 Asked in: Dec'22, June'25, Dec'25 — "define VM sizing, discuss two ways" repeats exactly</div>
<div class="sec">💡 Understand It Simply</div>
<div class="understand"><div class="ul">What it actually means</div><p>VM sizing means choosing exactly how much CPU, RAM, and storage to assign to a virtual machine — getting this right means your application runs efficiently without wasting resources. Too small = performance issues. Too big = wasteful spending. Two methods: increase the VM's own size (vertical) or add more VMs (horizontal).</p></div>
<div class="sec">🔑 Keywords to Memorise</div>
<div class="keywords"><div class="kl">These words MUST appear in your answer</div>
<div class="kw-grid"><span class="kw">Allocate resources to VM</span><span class="kw">Vertical VM sizing (Scale Up)</span><span class="kw">Horizontal VM sizing (Scale Out)</span><span class="kw">CPU RAM storage</span><span class="kw">Downtime required (vertical)</span><span class="kw">No downtime (horizontal)</span></div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 5-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>VM Sizing — Definition and Two Methods</span><span class="m5">5 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>VM Sizing is the process of determining the appropriate amount of <span class="kh">CPU, RAM, storage</span> to <span class="kh">allocate resources to VM</span> to efficiently run an application without over-provisioning or under-provisioning.</p>
<p><strong>Two Ways to do VM Sizing:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Vertical VM Sizing (Scale Up/Down):</strong> Increase or decrease the resources (CPU cores, RAM) of the existing VM itself. <span class="kh">Downtime required (vertical)</span> — VM must usually be stopped to add resources. Best for stateful applications.</li>
<li><strong>Horizontal VM Sizing (Scale Out/In):</strong> Add more VM instances of the same size to handle increased load. <span class="kh">No downtime (horizontal)</span> — new VMs added alongside existing ones. Best for stateless web applications.</li>
</ul>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 10-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>VM Sizing — Complete with Comparison Table</span><span class="m10">10 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>VM (Virtual Machine) Sizing is the process of identifying and <span class="kh">allocate resources to VM</span> the appropriate amount of <span class="kh">CPU, RAM, storage</span> for a VM to efficiently run its workload — balancing performance and cost.</p>
<table>
<tr><th>Feature</th><th>Vertical VM Sizing (Scale Up)</th><th>Horizontal VM Sizing (Scale Out)</th></tr>
<tr><td>Method</td><td>Increase resources of the SAME VM</td><td>Add MORE VM instances of same size</td></tr>
<tr><td>Downtime</td><td><span class="kh">Downtime required (vertical)</span> — VM must stop</td><td><span class="kh">No downtime (horizontal)</span> — new VMs added live</td></tr>
<tr><td>Limit</td><td>Limited by physical server capacity</td><td>Virtually unlimited — add as many VMs as needed</td></tr>
<tr><td>Cost</td><td>Higher per VM</td><td>More flexible cost management</td></tr>
<tr><td>Best For</td><td>Stateful databases and legacy applications</td><td>Stateless web apps, microservices</td></tr>
</table>
<p>Over-provisioning a VM wastes money and resources; under-provisioning leads to poor performance, high latency, and user dissatisfaction. Proper VM sizing based on workload analysis is essential for cost-efficient cloud operations.</p>
</div></div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ T7: RESOURCE SHARING & TENANCY ═══ -->
<div id="t7">
<div class="topic"><div class="tnum">7</div><div><div class="ttitle">Resource Sharing &amp; Multi-Tenancy</div><div class="tsub">Single Tenancy · Multi-Tenancy · Types · Tenancy at IaaS/PaaS/SaaS</div></div><span class="badge br">6+ Papers</span></div>
<div class="pyq">📋 Asked in: June'22, Dec'23, June'24, June'25 — "single tenancy vs multi-tenancy" and "tenancy at different levels" both repeat</div>
<div class="sec">💡 Understand It Simply</div>
<div class="understand"><div class="ul">What it actually means</div><p>Think of a building with apartments. Single tenancy = you own the entire building, no one else is there (your data never touches anyone else's). Multi-tenancy = multiple families share the same building but each has their own locked apartment (multiple customers share the same cloud infrastructure but are isolated from each other). Gmail is multi-tenant — millions of users share the same servers but can't see each other's emails.</p></div>
<div class="sec">🔑 Keywords to Memorise</div>
<div class="keywords"><div class="kl">These words MUST appear in your answer</div>
<div class="kw-grid"><span class="kw">Single tenancy — dedicated resources</span><span class="kw">Multi-tenancy — shared instance</span><span class="kw">Logical isolation</span><span class="kw">Single application multiple users</span><span class="kw">Cost efficiency</span><span class="kw">Multi-tenancy at IaaS level</span><span class="kw">Multi-tenancy at PaaS level</span><span class="kw">Multi-tenancy at SaaS level</span></div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 5-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Resource Sharing — Single vs Multi-Tenancy</span><span class="m5">5 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Resource Sharing in cloud computing means multiple users share the same physical infrastructure while appearing to have dedicated resources.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Single Tenancy:</strong> One customer gets <span class="kh">dedicated resources</span> — their own dedicated servers, storage, and software instance. Maximum security, highest cost. Example: private bank cloud.</li>
<li><strong>Multi-Tenancy:</strong> <span class="kh">Single application multiple users</span> — one application instance serves many customers simultaneously with <span class="kh">logical isolation</span> between them. Lower cost, higher resource utilisation. Example: Gmail serves billions of users on shared infrastructure.</li>
</ul>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 10-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Multi-Tenancy — Types and Tenancy at Different Service Levels</span><span class="m10">10 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Multi-tenancy allows <span class="kh">single application multiple users</span> to share one software instance while maintaining <span class="kh">logical isolation</span> between them, improving <span class="kh">cost efficiency</span> for both provider and customer.</p>
<p><strong>Three Ways to Implement Multi-Tenancy:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Separate Database per Tenant:</strong> Each tenant has their own separate database but shares application code. Highest isolation, higher storage cost.</li>
<li><strong>Shared Database, Separate Schema:</strong> Tenants share database server but have separate schemas (table namespaces). Medium isolation and cost.</li>
<li><strong>Shared Database, Shared Schema:</strong> All tenants share same tables — a TenantID column distinguishes data. Lowest cost, lowest isolation — most risky.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Tenancy at Different Cloud Service Levels:</strong></p>
<table>
<tr><th>Level</th><th>How Multi-Tenancy is Implemented</th></tr>
<tr><td><strong>IaaS</strong></td><td><span class="kh">Multi-tenancy at IaaS level</span> — virtualization of resources; customers share the same physical servers but each gets isolated VMs</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>PaaS</strong></td><td><span class="kh">Multi-tenancy at PaaS level</span> — multiple applications from different vendors run on the same platform/runtime environment</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>SaaS</strong></td><td><span class="kh">Multi-tenancy at SaaS level</span> — a single application instance is shared by multiple customers with logical data isolation</td></tr>
</table>
</div></div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ T8: RESOURCE POOLING ═══ -->
<div id="t8">
<div class="topic"><div class="tnum">8</div><div><div class="ttitle">Resource Pooling</div><div class="tsub">Server Pools · Storage Pools · Network Pools · Architecture</div></div><span class="badge by">4+ Papers</span></div>
<div class="pyq">📋 Asked in: June'22 (resource pooling architecture), June'24 (server, storage, network pools) — two different angles</div>
<div class="sec">💡 Understand It Simply</div>
<div class="understand"><div class="ul">What it actually means</div><p>Resource pooling is like a shared taxi pool vs owning individual cars. Instead of every customer having their own dedicated server sitting idle, all servers are pooled together and allocated dynamically to whoever needs them right now. When you don't need them, they go back to the pool for someone else to use.</p></div>
<div class="sec">🔑 Keywords to Memorise</div>
<div class="keywords"><div class="kl">These words MUST appear in your answer</div>
