<!-- ═══ T9: RESOURCE PROVISIONING ═══ -->
<div id="t9">
<div class="topic"><div class="tnum">9</div><div><div class="ttitle">Resource Provisioning</div><div class="tsub">Static · Dynamic · Hybrid · Advantages and Disadvantages</div></div><span class="badge br">6+ Papers</span></div>
<div class="pyq">📋 Asked in: Dec'22, Dec'23, Dec'24, June'25, Dec'25 — "static vs dynamic resource provisioning" is one of the most repeated comparison questions</div>
<div class="sec">💡 Understand It Simply</div>
<div class="understand"><div class="ul">What it actually means</div><p>Resource provisioning means setting up and allocating servers for a customer. Static provisioning = you book a fixed table at a restaurant regardless of how many people come. Dynamic provisioning = the restaurant automatically gives you more tables when more guests arrive and removes them when guests leave. Cloud's biggest advantage is dynamic provisioning — you pay for exactly what you actually used.</p></div>
<div class="sec">🔑 Keywords to Memorise</div>
<div class="keywords"><div class="kl">These words MUST appear in your answer</div>
<div class="kw-grid"><span class="kw">Pre-allocated fixed resources</span><span class="kw">Dynamic — allocated on demand</span><span class="kw">Over-provisioning waste</span><span class="kw">Under-provisioning poor performance</span><span class="kw">Hybrid provisioning</span><span class="kw">SLA (Service Level Agreement)</span><span class="kw">Pay-per-use</span></div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 5-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Resource Provisioning — Static vs Dynamic</span><span class="m5">5 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Resource Provisioning is the process of setting up and allocating cloud resources (servers, storage, network) to users to meet their requirements and maintain agreed <span class="kh">SLA (Service Level Agreement)</span>.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Static Provisioning:</strong> Resources are <span class="kh">pre-allocated fixed resources</span> in advance based on estimated peak demand. Simple to manage but leads to <span class="kh">over-provisioning waste</span> when demand is low.</li>
<li><strong>Dynamic Provisioning:</strong> Resources are <span class="kh">allocated on demand</span> automatically as workload changes. Enables <span class="kh">pay-per-use</span> billing. Avoids both over and under-provisioning.</li>
</ul>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 10-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Resource Provisioning — All Three Approaches with Comparison Table</span><span class="m10">10 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Resource Provisioning sets up and allocates cloud resources to meet user requirements and maintain <span class="kh">SLA (Service Level Agreement)</span>. Problems: <span class="kh">over-provisioning waste</span> (resources idle, money wasted) and <span class="kh">under-provisioning poor performance</span> (insufficient resources, users experience poor performance).</p>
<table>
<tr><th>Approach</th><th>How it Works</th><th>Advantage</th><th>Disadvantage</th></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Static</strong></td><td><span class="kh">Pre-allocated fixed resources</span> based on estimated peak demand. Resources remain reserved even when idle.</td><td>Simple to manage, predictable performance</td><td><span class="kh">Over-provisioning waste</span> — pays for idle resources; inflexible</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Dynamic</strong></td><td>Resources <span class="kh">allocated on demand</span> automatically based on actual real-time workload. Scale up or down instantly.</td><td>Cost-efficient <span class="kh">pay-per-use</span>, no waste, handles spikes</td><td>More complex to implement; risk of <span class="kh">under-provisioning poor performance</span> if scaling is slow</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Hybrid</strong></td><td><span class="kh">Hybrid provisioning</span> combines static and dynamic — baseline is statically provisioned, peaks handled dynamically</td><td>Best of both: predictable baseline + flexible peaks</td><td>More complex to configure and manage</td></tr>
