<!-- ═══ T10: LOAD BALANCING ═══ -->
<div id="t10">
<div class="topic"><div class="tnum">10</div><div><div class="ttitle">Load Balancing</div><div class="tsub">Definition · Why Needed · Algorithms · Types of Load Balancers</div></div><span class="badge br">6+ Papers</span></div>
<div class="pyq">📋 Asked in: Dec'22, June'23, Dec'23, June'25, Dec'25 — "weighted round robin algorithm" and "hardware vs virtual load balancer" repeat frequently</div>
<div class="sec">💡 Understand It Simply</div>
<div class="understand"><div class="ul">What it actually means</div><p>Load balancing is like a traffic police officer at a busy intersection — instead of letting all cars pile into one lane and cause gridlock, the officer distributes cars evenly across all available lanes. Without load balancing, one server gets overwhelmed while others sit idle. With it, work is distributed evenly — all servers stay busy but none gets overloaded.</p></div>
<div class="sec">🔑 Keywords to Memorise</div>
<div class="keywords"><div class="kl">These words MUST appear in your answer</div>
<div class="kw-grid"><span class="kw">Distribute workload evenly</span><span class="kw">Avoid server overload</span><span class="kw">Static algorithm</span><span class="kw">Weighted Round Robin</span><span class="kw">Network load balancer</span><span class="kw">Application load balancer</span><span class="kw">Hardware-based load balancer</span><span class="kw">Virtual load balancer</span><span class="kw">High availability</span></div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 5-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Load Balancing — Definition and Algorithms</span><span class="m5">5 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Load Balancing is the process of <span class="kh">distributing workload evenly</span> across multiple servers in a cloud environment to <span class="kh">avoid server overload</span>, ensure <span class="kh">high availability</span>, and optimise resource utilisation.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Static Algorithm:</strong> <span class="kh">Static algorithm</span> — assigns tasks to servers based on a fixed pre-determined rule without considering current server load. Simple but inefficient when servers have different capacities.</li>
<li><strong>Weighted Round Robin:</strong> <span class="kh">Weighted Round Robin</span> — assigns a weight to each server based on its capacity. Servers with higher weights receive more requests proportionally. Example: Server A (weight 3) gets 3 requests for every 1 request Server B (weight 1) receives.</li>
</ul>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 10-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Load Balancing — Why Needed, Algorithms, and Types of Load Balancers</span><span class="m10">10 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Load Balancing <span class="kh">distributes workload evenly</span> across multiple servers to <span class="kh">avoid server overload</span>, maintain <span class="kh">high availability</span>, and optimise performance. Without load balancing, some servers would be overwhelmed while others sit idle.</p>
<p><strong>Why Load Balancing is Imperative in Cloud:</strong> Cloud applications serve thousands of concurrent users. A single server cannot handle all requests. If one server fails, others should seamlessly take over. Load balancing ensures fault tolerance, efficient resource utilisation, and consistent response times.</p>
<p><strong>Load Balancing Algorithms:</strong></p>
<table>
<tr><th>Algorithm</th><th>How it Works</th><th>Best For</th></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Static (Round Robin)</strong></td><td>Requests distributed in fixed sequential order — Server 1, Server 2, Server 3, repeat. Ignores current load.</td><td>Servers with identical capacity</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Weighted Round Robin</strong></td><td>Servers assigned weights per capacity. Higher weight = more requests. Example: Server A weight 3 gets 3 requests per round, Server B weight 1 gets 1.</td><td>Servers with different capacities</td></tr>
</table>
<p><strong>Types of Load Balancers:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Hardware-based Load Balancer:</strong> <span class="kh">Hardware-based load balancer</span> — dedicated physical appliance, high performance, very reliable, expensive. Used in large enterprises.</li>
<li><strong>Virtual Load Balancer:</strong> <span class="kh">Virtual load balancer</span> — software-based, runs as a VM, easily scalable, less expensive. Ideal for cloud environments.</li>
<li><strong>Network Load Balancer:</strong> <span class="kh">Network load balancer</span> — operates at Layer 4 (TCP/UDP), fast, handles millions of requests per second, no content inspection.</li>
<li><strong>Application Load Balancer:</strong> <span class="kh">Application load balancer</span> — operates at Layer 7 (HTTP/HTTPS), content-aware routing, can redirect based on URL path or headers.</li>
</ul>
</div></div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ T11: SCALING STRATEGIES ═══ -->
<div id="t11">
<div class="topic"><div class="tnum">11</div><div><div class="ttitle">Scaling Strategies</div><div class="tsub">Proactive · Reactive · Combinational · Vertical vs Horizontal Scaling</div></div><span class="badge br">7+ Papers</span></div>
<div class="pyq">📋 Asked in: Dec'22, June'23, Dec'23, June'24, Dec'24, June'25, Dec'25 — "proactive vs reactive scaling comparison table" appears in almost every paper</div>
<div class="sec">💡 Understand It Simply</div>
<div class="understand"><div class="ul">What it actually means</div><p>Proactive scaling = you check the weather forecast and take an umbrella before it rains (you add servers before you expect a traffic spike). Reactive scaling = you wait until it's already raining and then look for an umbrella (servers are added after traffic already spiked — users experience a brief lag). Vertical = make your one server bigger. Horizontal = add more servers alongside.</p></div>
<div class="sec">🔑 Keywords to Memorise</div>
<div class="keywords"><div class="kl">These words MUST appear in your answer</div>
<div class="kw-grid"><span class="kw">Proactive — forecast based</span><span class="kw">Reactive — threshold based</span><span class="kw">Combinational scaling</span><span class="kw">Vertical scaling (Scale Up)</span><span class="kw">Horizontal scaling (Scale Out)</span><span class="kw">Elasticity</span><span class="kw">Scale up threshold</span><span class="kw">Scale down threshold</span><span class="kw">Ping-pong effect</span></div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 5-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Scaling Strategies — Quick Version</span><span class="m5">5 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Scaling is the process of dynamically adjusting cloud resources to meet changing demand — exploiting cloud <span class="kh">elasticity</span>.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Proactive Scaling:</strong> <span class="kh">Proactive — forecast based</span> — resources provisioned BEFORE expected load surge based on traffic patterns or schedule. No lag but may over-provision.</li>
<li><strong>Reactive Scaling:</strong> <span class="kh">Reactive — threshold based</span> — resources added AFTER actual load exceeds a threshold. Users experience brief lag during scaling. Cost efficient but delayed.</li>
<li><strong>Vertical Scaling:</strong> <span class="kh">Vertical scaling (Scale Up)</span> — increase resources of existing server (more CPU, RAM). Limited by hardware limits.</li>
<li><strong>Horizontal Scaling:</strong> <span class="kh">Horizontal scaling (Scale Out)</span> — add more servers. Virtually unlimited scalability.</li>
</ul>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 10-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Scaling Strategies — Complete Comparison with Proactive, Reactive, Combinational</span><span class="m10">10 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Scaling adjusts cloud resources dynamically using cloud <span class="kh">elasticity</span> to handle varying demand efficiently.</p>
<table>
<tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Proactive Scaling</th><th>Reactive Scaling</th></tr>
<tr><td>Basis</td><td><span class="kh">Proactive — forecast based</span> — based on predicted/scheduled load</td><td><span class="kh">Reactive — threshold based</span> — triggered when actual load crosses threshold</td></tr>
<tr><td>Timing</td><td>Resources added BEFORE load arrives</td><td>Resources added AFTER load exceeds threshold</td></tr>
<tr><td>User Experience</td><td>No lag — resources ready in advance</td><td>Brief lag during scaling while new resources start</td></tr>
<tr><td>Cost</td><td>May over-provision if estimate is wrong</td><td>Pay only for what is actually used</td></tr>
<tr><td>Suitability</td><td>Known traffic patterns (e.g., weekend spikes, sale events)</td><td>Unknown or unpredictable traffic patterns</td></tr>
<tr><td>Implementation</td><td>Requires traffic forecasting and scheduling</td><td>Simpler — define thresholds, system does rest</td></tr>
</table>
<p><strong>Combinational Scaling:</strong> <span class="kh">Combinational scaling</span> combines both — proactively scales for predicted load while also reactively handling unexpected spikes. Best performance with lowest unnecessary cost.</p>
<p><strong>Vertical vs Horizontal Scaling:</strong></p>
<table>
<tr><th>Feature</th><th>Vertical (Scale Up)</th><th>Horizontal (Scale Out)</th></tr>
<tr><td>Method</td><td>Add more CPU/RAM to existing server</td><td>Add more server instances</td></tr>
<tr><td>Limit</td><td>Limited by physical server max</td><td>Virtually unlimited</td></tr>
<tr><td>Downtime</td><td>Usually requires restart</td><td>No downtime — adds seamlessly</td></tr>
</table>
<p>The <span class="kh">ping-pong effect</span> occurs in auto-scaling when rapid alternating scale-up and scale-down decisions occur due to the threshold being set too close to the current load level — avoided by maintaining a "cool-down period" between scaling actions.</p>
</div></div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ T12: AUTO SCALING ALGORITHM ═══ -->
<div id="t12">
<div class="topic"><div class="tnum">12</div><div><div class="ttitle">Auto Scaling Algorithm</div><div class="tsub">Fixed Amount Auto Scaling · Algorithm Steps · Example</div></div><span class="badge by">4+ Papers</span></div>
<div class="pyq">📋 Asked in: June'22, June'25 — "write and explain fixed amount auto scaling algorithm" asked exactly</div>
<div class="sec">💡 Understand It Simply</div>
<div class="understand"><div class="ul">What it actually means</div><p>Auto-scaling is the cloud's automatic "thermostat" — it monitors how busy the servers are, and when they get too busy, it adds a fixed number of new servers. When traffic drops, it removes that same fixed number. The algorithm has specific thresholds (like temperature settings on a thermostat) that trigger these scale-up and scale-down decisions.</p></div>
<div class="sec">🔑 Keywords to Memorise</div>
<div class="keywords"><div class="kl">These words MUST appear in your answer</div>
<div class="kw-grid"><span class="kw">RPS (Requests Per Second)</span><span class="kw">Scale-up threshold (T_U)</span><span class="kw">Scale-down threshold (T_D)</span><span class="kw">Fixed amount U (scale up) D (scale down)</span><span class="kw">Cooldown period</span><span class="kw">N_min minimum nodes</span><span class="kw">Ping-pong effect</span></div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 10-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Fixed Amount Auto Scaling Algorithm — Steps and Example</span><span class="m10">10 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Auto Scaling automatically adjusts the number of VM instances based on current load, using defined <span class="kh">scale-up threshold (T_U)</span> and <span class="kh">scale-down threshold (T_D)</span> measured in <span class="kh">RPS (Requests Per Second)</span> per node.</p>
<p><strong>Fixed Amount Auto Scaling Algorithm:</strong></p>
<div class="formula">Algorithm: Fixed Amount Auto Scaling
Input: SLA-specific application
Parameters:
  N_min = minimum number of nodes
  U     = scale up value (fixed amount to add)
  D     = scale down value (fixed amount to remove)
  T_U   = scale up threshold (= 0.90 × T(SLA))
  T_D   = scale down threshold (= 0.50 × T_U)

Scale Up (when RPS_n > T_U):
  Repeat:
    N_c ← N_c + U
    RPS_n ← RPS_n × (old N_c / new N_c)
  Until RPS_n ≤ T_U

Scale Down (when RPS_n < T_D):
  Repeat:
    N_c ← max(N_min, N_c - D)
    RPS_n ← RPS_n × (old N_c / new N_c)
  Until RPS_n ≥ T_D or N_c = N_min</div>
<p><strong>Example Trace:</strong> Let U=2, D=2, T_U=120, T_D=60. Start: 4 nodes, RPS=450, RPS_n=112.5. When RPS surges to 1800:</p>
<table>
<tr><th>Nodes (before)</th><th>Nodes Added</th><th>Total Nodes</th><th>New RPS_n</th></tr>
<tr><td>4</td><td>2</td><td>6</td><td>300</td></tr>
<tr><td>6</td><td>2</td><td>8</td><td>313.75</td></tr>
<tr><td>8</td><td>2</td><td>10</td><td>330</td></tr>
</table>
<p>A <span class="kh">cooldown period</span> is mandatory between scaling actions to allow the new nodes to start handling traffic before the next scaling decision is made — preventing the <span class="kh">ping-pong effect</span> (rapid oscillation between scale-up and scale-down). <span class="kh">N_min minimum nodes</span> ensures the system never scales down below the minimum required to maintain basic service.</p>
</div></div>
</div>
<!-- ═══ T13: CLOUD SECURITY ═══ -->
<div id="t13">
<div class="topic"><div class="tnum">13</div><div><div class="ttitle">Cloud Security</div><div class="tsub">Threats · Security Mechanisms · Identity Management · SECaaS</div></div><span class="badge by">5+ Papers</span></div>
