</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 10-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>IoT — Definition, Characteristics, Categories, and M2M vs IoT</span><span class="m10">10 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>IoT is a massive network of physical devices embedded with <span class="kh">sensors, software, electronics, and network</span> connectivity enabling device-to-device communication without human interaction. By 2020, an estimated <span class="kh">50 billion devices</span> were connected to internet.</p>
<p><strong>5 Characteristics:</strong> <span class="kh">Dynamic and self-adapting</span>, <span class="kh">Self-configuring</span>, <span class="kh">Interoperable communication protocols</span>, <span class="kh">Unique identity (IP address)</span>, Integrated into Information Network.</p>
<p><strong>Four Categories of IoT:</strong></p>
<table>
<tr><th>Category</th><th>Description</th><th>Example</th></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Consumer IoT</strong></td><td>Smart home, wearables, personal devices. Uses Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, ZigBee.</td><td>Smart speaker, fitness tracker, smart TV</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Industrial IoT (IIoT)</strong></td><td>Manufacturing, agriculture, healthcare — increasing productivity and efficiency</td><td>Factory sensors, precision farming, remote patient monitoring</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Infrastructure IoT</strong></td><td>Smart infrastructure — bridges, railway tracks, wind farms</td><td>Bridge stress sensors, smart traffic systems</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Internet of Military Things (IoMT)</strong></td><td>Military applications — situational awareness, drones, connected soldiers</td><td>Connected tanks, drones, soldier health monitors</td></tr>
</table>
<p><strong>M2M vs IoT:</strong> M2M (Machine-to-Machine) is point-to-point communication between two specific devices over dedicated networks (e.g., ATM communicating with bank server). IoT is broader — devices connect over open internet, are addressable individually, and interact with a wide ecosystem of services and data platforms. IoT requires internet connectivity; M2M can work over private networks.</p>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 20-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>IoT — Complete: All Characteristics, Categories, Components, Technologies</span><span class="m20">20 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>IoT is a massive network of physical devices embedded with <span class="kh">sensors, software, electronics, and network</span> connectivity. It enables devices to collect data, communicate, and act autonomously without human interaction. By 2020, an estimated <span class="kh">50 billion devices</span> were connected globally.</p>
<p><strong>5 Characteristics:</strong> <span class="kh">Dynamic and self-adapting</span> (surveillance systems adapt to context), <span class="kh">Self-configuring</span> (devices work together automatically), <span class="kh">Interoperable communication protocols</span> (can talk to different systems), <span class="kh">Unique identity (IP address)</span> (each device uniquely addressable), Integrated into Information Network (seamless data exchange).</p>
<p><strong>Four IoT Categories:</strong> <span class="kh">Consumer IoT</span> (smart home, wearables), <span class="kh">Industrial IoT (IIoT)</span> (factories, healthcare, logistics), <span class="kh">Infrastructure IoT</span> (bridges, smart cities), <span class="kh">Internet of Military Things (IoMT)</span> (battlefield awareness, connected soldiers).</p>
<p><strong>Four Components Supporting IoT System:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Sensing:</strong> Sensors collect physical world data (temperature, motion, light, pressure)</li>
<li><strong>Network:</strong> Connectivity layer (Wi-Fi, Zigbee, LTE, 5G) transmits sensor data to cloud/edge</li>
<li><strong>Data Processing:</strong> Cloud or edge computing analyses sensor data and generates insights</li>
<li><strong>Action:</strong> Actuators execute decisions — motors, valves, alerts based on processed data</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>10 Baseline/Emerging IoT Technologies (from textbook):</strong> IoT Security, IoT Analytics, IoT Device Management, Low-Power Short-Range Networks, Low-Power Wide-Area Networks, IoT Processors, IoT Operating Systems, Event Stream Processing, IoT Platforms, IoT Standards and Ecosystems.</p>
<p><strong>M2M vs IoT:</strong> M2M is point-to-point between two specific devices on private networks; IoT connects billions of devices over the open internet with unique addresses and cloud integration. IoT subsumes M2M but adds internet connectivity, cloud analytics, and device ecosystem management.</p>
</div></div>
