<!-- ═══ T15: SENSORS ═══ -->
<div id="t15">
<div class="topic"><div class="tnum">15</div><div><div class="ttitle">IoT Sensors</div><div class="tsub">Definition · Characteristics · Types of Sensors</div></div><span class="badge by">5+ Papers</span></div>
<div class="pyq">📋 Asked in: Dec'22, June'23, Dec'23, June'25 — "define sensor, explain characteristics, explain 4 types" repeats exactly</div>
<div class="sec">💡 Understand It Simply</div>
<div class="understand"><div class="ul">What it actually means</div><p>A sensor is the "nose," "eye," or "ear" of an IoT device — it detects something in the physical world (temperature, light, movement, chemicals) and converts it into an electrical signal that can be measured and sent to a computer. Without sensors, IoT devices would be blind to the real world.</p></div>
<div class="sec">🔑 Keywords to Memorise</div>
<div class="keywords"><div class="kl">These words MUST appear in your answer</div>
<div class="kw-grid"><span class="kw">Usable output in response to measurement</span><span class="kw">Sensitivity</span><span class="kw">Resolution</span><span class="kw">Linearity</span><span class="kw">Drift</span><span class="kw">Range</span><span class="kw">Image sensor</span><span class="kw">Chemical sensor</span><span class="kw">Acceleration sensor</span><span class="kw">Proximity sensor</span></div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 5-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Sensors — Definition and Key Characteristics</span><span class="m5">5 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>A sensor is a device that provides a <span class="kh">usable output in response to measurement</span> — it detects a physical parameter and converts it into a signal suitable for processing (electrical, mechanical, or optical).</p>
<p><strong>Key Static Characteristics of Sensors:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Sensitivity:</strong> <span class="kh">Sensitivity</span> — change in output per unit change in input (e.g., 89 dB SPL/W/m for a speaker)</li>
<li><strong>Resolution:</strong> <span class="kh">Resolution</span> — smallest detectable change in input (e.g., ruler resolution = 1mm)</li>
<li><strong>Range:</strong> <span class="kh">Range</span> — allowed lower and upper limits of input the sensor can detect accurately</li>
<li><strong>Linearity:</strong> <span class="kh">Linearity</span> — degree to which output is proportional to input (calibration curve)</li>
<li><strong>Drift:</strong> <span class="kh">Drift</span> — deviation in sensor output over time when input is kept constant</li>
</ul>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 10-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>IoT Sensors — Definition, Characteristics, and 4 Types with Applications</span><span class="m10">10 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>A sensor is a device that provides a <span class="kh">usable output in response to measurement</span> — it attains a physical parameter and converts it into a signal suitable for processing. Sensors are the components that provide actionable insights and power IoT systems.</p>
<p><strong>Static Characteristics:</strong> <span class="kh">Sensitivity</span> (output change per unit input change), <span class="kh">Resolution</span> (smallest detectable change), <span class="kh">Linearity</span> (calibration curve resembles straight line), <span class="kh">Drift</span> (deviation over time at constant input), <span class="kh">Range</span> (allowed input limits for accurate output).</p>
