<!-- ═══ T16: ACTUATORS ═══ -->
<div id="t16">
<div class="topic"><div class="tnum">16</div><div><div class="ttitle">IoT Actuators</div><div class="tsub">Definition · Types of Actuators</div></div><span class="badge by">4+ Papers</span></div>
<div class="pyq">📋 Asked in: Dec'22, Dec'23, June'25 — "define actuator, explain any 3-4 types" repeats</div>
<div class="sec">💡 Understand It Simply</div>
<div class="understand"><div class="ul">What it actually means</div><p>If a sensor is the "sense organ" of an IoT device, an actuator is the "muscle." A sensor detects (input), a processor decides, and an actuator acts (output). Your smart thermostat's temperature sensor detects cold room → processor decides to heat → actuator (the heating element) physically turns on the heat. No actuator = IoT can only sense, never act.</p></div>
<div class="sec">🔑 Keywords to Memorise</div>
<div class="keywords"><div class="kl">These words MUST appear in your answer</div>
<div class="kw-grid"><span class="kw">Converts control signal to physical action</span><span class="kw">Electric actuator</span><span class="kw">Hydraulic actuator</span><span class="kw">Pneumatic actuator</span><span class="kw">Thermal / Magnetic actuator</span><span class="kw">Mechanical actuator</span></div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 5-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Actuators — Definition and Types</span><span class="m5">5 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>An Actuator is an IoT component that <span class="kh">converts a control signal to physical action</span> — it receives a digital command and physically moves or controls a mechanism in the real world. Actuators are the "output" components of IoT systems that cause things to happen.</p>
<p><strong>Types of Actuators:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Electric Actuator:</strong> <span class="kh">Electric actuator</span> — uses electrical energy to produce mechanical movement. Most common — motors, solenoids. Example: electric car window mechanism.</li>
<li><strong>Hydraulic Actuator:</strong> <span class="kh">Hydraulic actuator</span> — uses pressurised liquid (oil/water) to generate powerful force. Example: construction machinery, aircraft landing gear.</li>
<li><strong>Pneumatic Actuator:</strong> <span class="kh">Pneumatic actuator</span> — uses compressed air to generate motion. Fast, clean, cheap. Example: pneumatic cylinder in manufacturing robots.</li>
<li><strong>Thermal/Magnetic Actuator:</strong> <span class="kh">Thermal / Magnetic actuator</span> — uses heat or magnetic field for activation. Example: bimetallic strip thermostat, magnetic valve.</li>
<li><strong>Mechanical Actuator:</strong> <span class="kh">Mechanical actuator</span> — converts rotary motion to linear motion (gears, pulleys, cams). Example: car steering mechanism.</li>
</ul>
</div></div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ T17: IoT PROTOCOLS ═══ -->
<div id="t17">
<div class="topic"><div class="tnum">17</div><div><div class="ttitle">IoT Communication Protocols</div><div class="tsub">MQTT · CoAP · XMPP · Zigbee · Z-Wave · RFID · NFC · IPv6</div></div><span class="badge br">7+ Papers</span></div>
<div class="pyq">📋 Asked in: June'22, Dec'22, Dec'23, June'24, Dec'25 — "MQTT, CoAP, XMPP" always a short note; "Zigbee, Z-Wave, RFID, NFC" always another</div>
<div class="sec">💡 Understand It Simply</div>
<div class="understand"><div class="ul">What it actually means</div><p>IoT devices need to "talk" to each other and to the cloud. But a tiny temperature sensor doesn't have the power to use heavy protocols like HTTP. These specialised IoT protocols are designed to be lightweight, low-power, and reliable over unreliable networks. MQTT is like sending short SMS messages (lightweight). CoAP is HTTP for tiny devices. Zigbee and Z-Wave are like walkie-talkies for smart home devices — short range but very energy efficient.</p></div>
<div class="sec">🔑 Keywords to Memorise</div>
<div class="keywords"><div class="kl">These words MUST appear in your answer</div>
<div class="kw-grid"><span class="kw">MQTT — publish/subscribe lightweight</span><span class="kw">CoAP — constrained devices HTTP-like</span><span class="kw">XMPP — XML-based messaging</span><span class="kw">Zigbee — low power mesh 250kbps</span><span class="kw">Z-Wave — home automation 868MHz</span><span class="kw">RFID — radio frequency identification</span><span class="kw">NFC — near field 13.56MHz</span><span class="kw">IPv6 — unique addressing</span></div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 5-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>MQTT, CoAP, XMPP — Quick Version</span><span class="m5">5 Marks</span></div>
