<ul>
<li><strong>MQTT (Message Queuing Telemetry Transport):</strong> <span class="kh">MQTT — publish/subscribe lightweight</span> protocol. Devices publish messages to a "broker," other devices subscribe to receive them. Very low bandwidth, works over unreliable networks. Ideal for IoT sensors with limited power. Example: smart meter publishing electricity readings.</li>
<li><strong>CoAP (Constrained Application Protocol):</strong> <span class="kh">CoAP — constrained devices HTTP-like</span> protocol. Designed for microcontrollers and constrained environments. Similar to HTTP but much lighter (uses UDP). Example: smart light bulbs.</li>
<li><strong>XMPP (Extensible Messaging and Presence Protocol):</strong> <span class="kh">XMPP — XML-based messaging</span> protocol. Originally for chat, now used for real-time IoT messaging. Supports device presence detection. Example: smart home automation messages.</li>
</ul>
</div></div>

