<!-- ═══ T18: IoT SECURITY ═══ -->
<div id="t18">
<div class="topic"><div class="tnum">18</div><div><div class="ttitle">IoT Security</div><div class="tsub">Challenges · Threats · Mitigation Strategies</div></div><span class="badge by">5+ Papers</span></div>
<div class="pyq">📋 Asked in: Dec'22, June'24, Dec'24, Dec'25 — "IoT security challenges" and "mitigation strategies" repeat as short notes and full questions</div>
<div class="sec">💡 Understand It Simply</div>
<div class="understand"><div class="ul">What it actually means</div><p>IoT devices are everywhere — in hospitals, power grids, smart homes, even cars. But most have very weak security: simple passwords, outdated software, limited processing power for encryption. A hacked smart thermostat might seem harmless, but a hacked hospital IoT device could be life-threatening. Securing billions of low-power, distributed devices is the hardest security problem of the IoT era.</p></div>
<div class="sec">🔑 Keywords to Memorise</div>
<div class="keywords"><div class="kl">These words MUST appear in your answer</div>
<div class="kw-grid"><span class="kw">Limited computational resources</span><span class="kw">Heterogeneous devices</span><span class="kw">Physical tampering</span><span class="kw">Denial of Sleep attacks</span><span class="kw">Encryption</span><span class="kw">Secure device management</span><span class="kw">Regular software updates</span><span class="kw">Authentication</span><span class="kw">Intrusion Detection</span></div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 5-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>IoT Security — Key Challenges</span><span class="m5">5 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p><strong>Key IoT Security Challenges:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Limited Computational Resources:</strong> <span class="kh">Limited computational resources</span> — IoT devices have tiny CPUs and RAM, making strong encryption computationally expensive or impossible</li>
<li><strong>Heterogeneous Devices:</strong> <span class="kh">Heterogeneous devices</span> — billions of different devices, operating systems, and protocols make uniform security standards extremely difficult</li>
<li><strong>Physical Tampering:</strong> <span class="kh">Physical tampering</span> — IoT devices deployed in public/remote locations can be physically accessed and compromised by attackers</li>
<li><strong>Denial of Sleep Attacks:</strong> <span class="kh">Denial of Sleep attacks</span> — attackers prevent battery-powered IoT devices from entering sleep mode, draining their batteries rapidly</li>
<li><strong>Insecure Updates:</strong> Many IoT devices lack secure firmware update mechanisms, leaving known vulnerabilities unpatched for years</li>
</ul>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 10-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>IoT Security — Challenges and Mitigation Strategies</span><span class="m10">10 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p><strong>Key IoT Security Challenges:</strong></p>
<table>
<tr><th>Challenge</th><th>Description</th></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Limited Computational Resources</strong></td><td>Simple processors can't run heavy encryption algorithms — security is compromised for efficiency</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Heterogeneous Devices</strong></td><td>Billions of devices with different OS, protocols, manufacturers — no unified security standard</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Physical Tampering</strong></td><td>Devices in remote/public locations can be physically accessed, cloned, or modified</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Denial of Sleep Attacks</strong></td><td>Attackers prevent power-saving sleep mode — drains battery, makes device unreachable</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Insecure APIs and Interfaces</strong></td><td>Poorly designed web/cloud interfaces expose devices to remote attacks</td></tr>
</table>
<p><strong>Mitigation Strategies:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Encryption:</strong> <span class="kh">Encryption</span> — use lightweight encryption algorithms suitable for constrained IoT devices (e.g., AES-128 instead of AES-256)</li>
<li><strong>Secure Device Management:</strong> <span class="kh">Secure device management</span> — centralised monitoring of all IoT devices, detecting anomalies, enforcing security policies</li>
<li><strong>Regular Software Updates:</strong> <span class="kh">Regular software updates</span> — automated over-the-air firmware updates to patch vulnerabilities quickly</li>
<li><strong>Strong Authentication:</strong> <span class="kh">Authentication</span> — replace default passwords, use certificate-based authentication for device identity</li>
<li><strong>Intrusion Detection:</strong> <span class="kh">Intrusion Detection</span> — monitor network traffic for attack patterns; isolate compromised devices automatically</li>
</ul>
</div></div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ T19: EDGE & FOG COMPUTING ═══ -->
<div id="t19">
<div class="topic"><div class="tnum">19</div><div><div class="ttitle">Edge Computing &amp; Fog Computing</div><div class="tsub">Edge vs Cloud vs Fog · 3-Layer Fog Architecture · Use Cases · Advantages</div></div><span class="badge br">ALL Papers</span></div>
<div class="pyq">📋 Asked in: June'22, Dec'22, June'23, Dec'23, June'24, Dec'24, June'25, Dec'25 — appears in EVERY paper in various forms — fog definition, edge architecture, cloud vs fog vs edge comparison</div>
<div class="sec">💡 Understand It Simply</div>
<div class="understand"><div class="ul">What it actually means</div><p>Cloud computing processes data far away in distant data centres (high latency). Edge computing processes data right at the device itself — a self-driving car cannot wait 500ms for a cloud server to decide whether to brake. Fog computing is the middle layer — process data at local gateways and routers near devices, not as close as edge, not as far as cloud. Cloud = central kitchen. Fog = local restaurant. Edge = your own kitchen at home.</p></div>
<div class="sec">🔑 Keywords to Memorise</div>
<div class="keywords"><div class="kl">These words MUST appear in your answer</div>
<div class="kw-grid"><span class="kw">Edge — processing at the device</span><span class="kw">Low latency</span><span class="kw">Reduced bandwidth</span><span class="kw">Fog — intermediate layer</span><span class="kw">3-layer fog architecture</span><span class="kw">Terminal layer</span><span class="kw">Fog layer</span><span class="kw">Cloud layer</span><span class="kw">Real-time decision making</span></div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 5-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Edge vs Fog Computing — Quick Version</span><span class="m5">5 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p><strong>Edge Computing:</strong> Processes data at or near the IoT device itself — at the "<span class="kh">edge</span>" of the network. Benefits: <span class="kh">low latency</span> (no data travel time to cloud), <span class="kh">reduced bandwidth</span> (only relevant data sent to cloud), <span class="kh">real-time decision making</span>. Use cases: self-driving cars, real-time industrial monitoring.</p>
<p><strong>Fog Computing:</strong> An <span class="kh">intermediate layer</span> between IoT devices and the cloud — processing at local gateways, routers, or edge servers. Has a <span class="kh">3-layer fog architecture</span>: Terminal Layer (IoT devices) → Fog Layer (local processing) → Cloud Layer (heavy analytics). Provides <span class="kh">low latency</span> with more resources than pure edge devices.</p>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 10-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Edge and Fog Computing — Architecture, Advantages, and Cloud-Fog-Edge Comparison</span><span class="m10">10 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p><strong>Edge Computing</strong> processes data at the point of generation — the IoT device or gateway itself — without sending to the cloud. This gives <span class="kh">low latency</span>, <span class="kh">reduced bandwidth</span>, privacy (data stays local), and <span class="kh">real-time decision making</span>.</p>
<p><strong>Fog Computing — 3-Layer Architecture:</strong></p>
<div class="dia"><svg viewBox="0 0 500 175" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" font-family="Inter,sans-serif" style="max-width:480px;width:100%">
<rect x="10" y="8" width="480" height="44" rx="7" fill="#292205" stroke="#fbbf24" stroke-width="1.5"/>
<text x="250" y="27" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fde68a" font-size="11" font-weight="700">CLOUD LAYER</text>
<text x="250" y="45" text-anchor="middle" fill="#94a3b8" font-size="9">Big data analytics · Long-term storage · Machine learning · Global management</text>
<rect x="10" y="65" width="480" height="44" rx="7" fill="#0d2e1a" stroke="#4ade80" stroke-width="1.5"/>
<text x="250" y="84" text-anchor="middle" fill="#86efac" font-size="11" font-weight="700">FOG LAYER (Intermediate)</text>
<text x="250" y="100" text-anchor="middle" fill="#94a3b8" font-size="9">Local gateways · Routers · Edge servers · Pre-processing · Filtering</text>
<rect x="10" y="122" width="480" height="44" rx="7" fill="#2a1508" stroke="#fb923c" stroke-width="1.5"/>
<text x="250" y="141" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fdba74" font-size="11" font-weight="700">TERMINAL LAYER (IoT Devices)</text>
<text x="250" y="157" text-anchor="middle" fill="#94a3b8" font-size="9">Sensors · Actuators · Embedded devices · Smart meters</text>
</svg></div>
<p><strong>Cloud vs Fog vs Edge Comparison:</strong></p>
<table>
<tr><th>Feature</th><th>Cloud</th><th>Fog</th><th>Edge</th></tr>
<tr><td>Location</td><td>Remote data centre</td><td>Local gateway/router</td><td>At the device itself</td></tr>
<tr><td>Latency</td><td>High (100s ms)</td><td>Medium (10s ms)</td><td>Very low (&lt;1ms)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Resources</td><td>Unlimited</td><td>Moderate</td><td>Very limited</td></tr>
<tr><td>Data Scope</td><td>Global, all data</td><td>Local area</td><td>Single device</td></tr>
<tr><td>Use Case</td><td>Big data analytics</td><td>Smart city, factory</td><td>Self-driving car, AR</td></tr>
</table>
<p><strong>Advantages of Fog Computing:</strong> Reduces cloud bandwidth requirements, Low latency for time-critical applications, Works even when internet connectivity is interrupted, Better data privacy (sensitive data processed locally), Distributes processing load geographically.</p>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 20-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Edge and Fog Computing — Complete with Use Cases and Challenges</span><span class="m20">20 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p><strong>Edge Computing:</strong> Processing at or near the data source — at the "<span class="kh">edge</span>" of the network. Eliminates round-trip to cloud for time-critical decisions. Key advantages: <span class="kh">low latency</span>, <span class="kh">reduced bandwidth</span>, data privacy, <span class="kh">real-time decision making</span>, works offline when cloud connectivity fails.</p>
<p><strong>Fog Computing:</strong> An <span class="kh">intermediate layer</span> between IoT devices and cloud. Uses local compute infrastructure (gateways, routers, edge servers) to pre-process and filter data before sending relevant results to cloud.</p>
<p><strong>3-Layer Fog Architecture:</strong> <span class="kh">Terminal layer</span> (IoT devices — sensors, actuators, embedded systems) → <span class="kh">Fog layer</span> (local gateways, edge servers — pre-processing, caching, filtering) → <span class="kh">Cloud layer</span> (global data centre — big data analytics, long-term storage, ML model training).</p>
<p><strong>Cloud-Fog-Edge Collaboration:</strong> In a smart city: traffic sensors (Edge — real-time local signal adjustment) → city district gateways (Fog — aggregate and filter data, coordinate district-level traffic flow) → cloud (analyse city-wide patterns, long-term optimisation, prediction models).</p>
<p><strong>Use Cases of Edge Computing:</strong> Self-driving cars (must detect pedestrians in milliseconds — cannot wait for cloud), AR/VR (low latency rendering), Industrial robotics (real-time control), Healthcare monitors (instant patient alerts), Smart grid management.</p>
<p><strong>Challenges of Fog Computing:</strong> Resource management (fog nodes have limited compute), Security (fog nodes are distributed and harder to protect than centralised cloud), Scalability (managing thousands of fog nodes), Standardisation (no universal fog computing standard yet), Reliability (fog nodes may fail — need redundancy).</p>
<p><strong>Applications of Fog Computing:</strong> Smart traffic management, Smart meters (energy usage analytics), Healthcare real-time monitoring, Connected vehicles, Industrial automation, Smart buildings (HVAC control).</p>
</div></div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ T20: GRID vs CLUSTER vs CLOUD ═══ -->
<div id="t20">
<div class="topic"><div class="tnum">20</div><div><div class="ttitle">Grid vs Cluster vs Cloud Computing</div><div class="tsub">Characteristics · Hardware · Physical Structure · Networking · Scalability</div></div><span class="badge by">5+ Papers</span></div>
<div class="pyq">📋 Asked in: June'22, June'23, Dec'22 — "compare cluster, grid, cloud computing" table question repeats</div>
<div class="sec">💡 Understand It Simply</div>
<div class="understand"><div class="ul">What it actually means</div><p>Three different ways to use many computers together. Cluster = a team of identical players in the same room (tightly coupled, same hardware, same location). Grid = a global team where players are scattered worldwide and bring their own equipment (loosely coupled, different hardware, different locations). Cloud = a taxi service — you don't know or own the car; you just pay for the ride when you need it.</p></div>
<div class="sec">🔑 Keywords to Memorise</div>
<div class="keywords"><div class="kl">These words MUST appear in your answer</div>
<div class="kw-grid"><span class="kw">Cluster — tightly coupled</span><span class="kw">Grid — loosely coupled decentralized</span><span class="kw">Cloud — dynamic IT service-centric</span><span class="kw">Same hardware (cluster)</span><span class="kw">Different hardware (grid)</span><span class="kw">Pay-per-use (cloud)</span><span class="kw">Scalability</span></div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 10-Mark Answer</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Cluster vs Grid vs Cloud — Complete Comparison Table</span><span class="m10">10 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<table>
<tr><th>Feature</th><th>Cluster Computing</th><th>Grid Computing</th><th>Cloud Computing</th></tr>
<tr><td>Characteristics</td><td><span class="kh">Cluster — tightly coupled</span> systems; single system image; centralised job management</td><td><span class="kh">Grid — loosely coupled decentralized</span>; diversity and dynamism; distributed job management</td><td><span class="kh">Cloud — dynamic IT service-centric</span>; self-service usage; consumption-based billing</td></tr>
<tr><td>Physical Structure</td><td>Same physical location; directly connected with high-speed connections</td><td>Computers not in same location; operated independently</td><td>Computers need not be in same physical location</td></tr>
<tr><td>Hardware</td><td>All same hardware and OS — <span class="kh">same hardware (cluster)</span></td><td>Can run different OS and <span class="kh">different hardware (grid)</span></td><td>Memory, storage managed by cloud OS; uses open-source Linux</td></tr>
<tr><td>Billing</td><td>Fixed infrastructure cost</td><td>Free (donated resources model)</td><td><span class="kh">Pay-per-use (cloud)</span></td></tr>
<tr><td>Scalability</td><td>Limited (add same-spec machines only)</td><td>High (add any machine anywhere)</td><td>Highest — <span class="kh">scalability</span> on demand, instant</td></tr>
<tr><td>Application</td><td>HPC, scientific simulation</td><td>Large scientific projects (SETI@home)</td><td>Enterprise apps, web services, any workload</td></tr>
</table>
</div></div>
